e transnational economics of the apparel industry allow firms to relocate or subcontract their work anywhere in the world, making it much harder for garment workers in the United States or any other country to demand fair pay and humane working conditions. Putting a human face on globalization, Threads shows not only how international trade affects local communities but also how workers can organize in this new environment to more effectively demand better treatment from their distant corporate employers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBusiness. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  agender and sexuality, labor, power, globalization, global industry, apparel, clothing, clothes, sociology, social sciences, working conditions, factory work, sweatshops, stereotypes, united states of america, american business, mexican workers, mexico, western world, managers, worker, producers, consumers, production, transnational economy, international relations, fair pay, humane treatment, political organizing, politics, liz claiborne, aguascalientes, virginia, case study.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226113739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226113739/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles